    "Upon doing so, we appeal to recent anti-concentration inequalities of Rudelson and Vershynin [2008] of Littlewood-Offord-type, typical in modern random matrix theory; e.g.",
    "Tao andVu [2009, 2010] for random variables on [0, 1], showing that our bound is tight.",
    "In either case, we integrate techniques from (universal) approximation theory of neural networks with learning theoretic and random matrix theoretic tools to derive our results.",
    "This shows how not only the results, but also that techniques previously isolated within approximation theory can have learning theoretic applications.",
    "Related WorksA Zoo of LoRAs Following its introduction, numerous LoRA variants have emerged, often aiming to further reduce computational overhead."
